<font color="#FF0000">COULD WE WIN?</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 15 21:44:39 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
I don't agree on two issues. <br><br>
Shouting on the streets was mostly done by the young, college <br>
aged people. That is true, but the anti-war movement was<br>
much more than protests on the streets. It was letter <br>
writing campaigns, a general movement of ideas that <br>
was talked about and argued over at every kitchen table <br>
in America. A movement is not an organization, but many<br>
people, each in their unique way working towards a common<br>
objective. In this case the end of the war. I know a doctor<br>
who was in his 50's at the time was willing to stretch<br>
the point that he would write a medical reason to help<br>
someone avoid the draft. He was generally a conservative, <br>
but the  influence of the movement made him move the<br>
point which he would not go beyond in favor of those <br>
who wanted to avoid the draft. He became part of a movement <br>
by doing that. He never joined an organization, protested<br>
or considered himself &quot;anti-war&quot;. That is the group of<br>
people that held the most sway in the war. The middle<br>
class, average american. <br><br>
As to our ability to win the war, I have questions about <br>
that.If we were willing to create a large parking lot called<br>
Vietnam, then yes. But I don't think that would count as<br>
winning. A war has an objective. Our objective was to <br>
subdue the Communists and maintain a political presence<br>
in VN that was under our influence. I don't think that we<br>
could have accomplished that. The political organization<br>
of the communists throughout VN was much more powerful than<br>
the corrupt SVN gov't could put together or than an outside force<br>
(the US) could do. Also there is the issue of guerilla<br>
( or people's) war. A major issue in a war is supply lines. When<br>
we went out from our main bases we had to build supply lines and extend <br>
that throught the country. The NVA and NLF had much more<br>
local support and were able to exist living with a meager<br>
supply line the support they received from the peasants.<br><br>
Another issue is that we were marked by our looks. It was<br>
clear that Americans were on a specific side. The Communist<br>
army was able to blend in with the people. Our vets had<br>
to be wary of every Vietnamese person, couldn't tell if<br>
a child was carrying a bomb or not. This makes it much harder<br>
to identify the enemy. US soldiers therefore had to be on guard <br>
100% of the time. Communist forces could blend in and move<br>
about much more freely.<br><br>
I believe Giap wrote a book on this subject that I would like to<br>
read. It is far from my area of expertise, and I would like<br>
to hear other theories on this. <br><br>
I think the other reason we could never win the war is<br>
that we could never get the support of the US people<br>
because the people we were supposed to be supporting were<br>
basically puppets and did not represent their people. This<br>
goes back to the question of why we were there and who <br>
were the idiots that got us there. It is much easier to<br>
win a just war than one without an ideology to stand <br>
behind. <br><br>
This is meant with no disrespect to those who fought. It<br>
is ment to question the leadership of this country and<br>
their actions. 
